about:
I am a systems guy, deeply interested in all aspects of creating mission critical enterprise software for analyzing and managing vast amounts of data.

I have spent much of the last decade on open source big data platforms both on-premise and in the public clouds. It has been a privilege to help shape the big data revolution where petabyte scale data processing and management is now well within the grasp of most enterprises.

But that is in the past. Our customers only want to increase the velocity with which they realize value from their data in their quest to be more data driven. I am excited by the applicability of disruptive modern data architectures such as lakehouse, data fabric and data mesh. 

The pendulum will continue to swing between centralization through data lakes and lake houses and the impending decentralization with data mesh. To paraphrase Stonebraker, in data models and in life change is the only constant, the trick is to have fun along the way and make every journey count.

name: Arun Menawat
title: CEO at Profound Medical Inc.
about:
Dr. Arun Menawat is Chairman and CEO of Profound Medical Inc. (NASDAQ:PROF, TSX:PRN), a commercial stage medical technology company that markets real-time MRI-guided thermal ultrasound systems for incision-free ablation of abnormal or cancerous tissue. Profound‚Äôs key product is the TULSA-PRO therapeutic system, designed for precise and customizable ablation of diseased prostate tissue.

Prior to joining Profound, Arun served as the Chairman and CEO of Novadaq Technologies Inc. for 13 years, guiding the company from a start-up to one of the fastest-growing, NASDAQ listed medical technology companies in North America, with a market cap of over $ 1 Billion USD. During his tenure, Novadaq pioneered the field of fluorescence imaging and built a powerful new ecosystem that provides clinically relevant imaging solutions to improve outcomes at multiple points throughout the patient care continuum.

Arun previously served as President of Cedara Software Corp., a company that developed the industry‚Äôs first medical imaging software platform. Under his leadership, Cedara achieved profitability and was ultimately acquired. Today, the company‚Äôs imaging platform and its big data collection are part of IBM‚Äôs Watson program.

Arun also serves as a member of the board of directors or advisor to growth oriented life science companies. Earlier in his career, Arun held executive positions at Tenneco Inc. and Hercules Inc. in the areas of business development, technology development and mergers/acquisitions. He obtained a Ph.D. in Chemical Engineering from the University of Maryland, and an Executive MBA from the J.L. Kellogg School of Management, Northwestern University.  In 2014, he was named the EY Ontario Entrepreneur of the Year in the health sciences category.

name: Christoph Lassner
title: 3D and 4D perception, rendering and generation.
about:
I am deeply curious about how we can build virtual representations for the real world that can be optimized and rendered efficiently to faithfully match our perception (visual and beyond; see for example my projects on Neural Assets, VEO, Neural 3D Video, NR-NeRF - links on my website). A lot of my work focuses on perception and rendering systems for humans, see for example TAVA, HVH, ARCH, NBF, UP. I created the human pose estimation system for Amazon Halo, which is part of a system to create a 3D model of your body using your smartphone. My team‚Äôs work at Meta on reconstructing and rendering radiance fields interactively was featured at Meta Connect 2022 and on CNET (co-presented with Zhao Dong et al.‚Äôs work on inverse rendering).

At the same time, I am very interested in the engineering challenges such systems create and was awarded an Honorable Mention at the ACM Multimedia Open-Source Software Competition 2016 for my work on decision forests. In 2021, I wrote the Pulsar renderer (now the sphere-based rendering backend for PyTorch3D) and would love to find better ways to use low-level autodifferentiation on GPUs.

If you would like to work together on challenges at the intersection of machine learning, computer graphics and computer vision (from modeling to engineering), please reach out!

I grew an interest in computers at the age of 7, learning about hypervisors and hardware technologies. At the age of 11, I was inspired by the concept of Chrome OS to get involved in low level systems, where I contributed to the Chromium and Chromium OS projects, which led to my father and I being invited to Google I/O 2012 by the Chrome OS team. Eventually, the Dart programming language came along, and I got deeply involved in the ecosystem, contributing to the language and standard library, and building core open source technologies. At the age of 14, I was hired by an IoT company called DGLogik to build an IoT platform that could scale across complex networks, launching my career in IoT. At DGLogik, I became deeply involved in Google's IoT technologies across multiple divisions, ultimately ending up working at Google on their IoT platform for their internal Real Estate. In 2024, I retired from the IoT data sphere and started Edera, a company that is making computing secure-by-design.
speaking_engagements: Podcast interview on securing cloud computing and AI by design; Guest on 'Last Week in AWS' podcast discussing tech career and container security; Featured in RedMonk conversation on container isolation and virtualization
notable_achievements: Founder & CTO of Edera, building simple hypervisor technology for modern workloads
reasoning: The founder demonstrates strong technical expertise and early career achievements, particularly in systems engineering and IoT. Their experience at Google and early contributions to major projects (Chromium OS, Dart) show technical depth. name: Paul Eremenko
title: Co-founder and CEO at P-1 AI
about:
Paul Eremenko is the co-founder and CEO of P-1 AI which aims to build an engineering AGI and put an AI engineer on every team at every industrial company on earth. Paul also serves on the board of directors of Eve Air Mobility (NYSE: EVEX), an Embraer Company, and as an advisor to the New Vista Capital, an aerospace-focused investment and advisory firm.

Previously, Paul was co-founder and CEO of Universal Hydrogen Co., a hydrogen aviation company which developed and flew, in 2023, the world's largest fuel-cell powered passenger aircraft. Prior to founding Universal Hydrogen, Paul was SVP & CTO at United Technologies Corp., where he led the 30,000-strong engineering function, as well as research, technology, and innovation activities across the company. He was responsible for the company's safety management system across the four aerospace and commercial businesses. He also led the technical due diligence for the UTC-Raytheon merger.

Before UTC, Paul was CTO at Airbus, where he spearheaded flight demonstrators for hybrid-electric propulsion, single-pilot cockpit, autonomy, urban air mobility, and model-based digital tools for aircraft design, manufacturing, and services. He was also the founding CEO of Acubed, the company's Silicon Valley innovation center, and set up the Airbus China Innovation Center in Shenzhen. Paul also served on the investment committee of Airbus Ventures and as chairman of APWorks Gmbh, an aerospace additive manufacturing company.

Prior to Airbus, he was Director of Engineering at Google, in the Advanced Technology & Projects (ATAP) organization, where he created and led Project Ara, an open modular smartphone platform.

Before Google, Paul headed the Tactical Technology Office (TTO) at the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA), the Pentagon‚Äôs principal engine for disruptive innovation. TTO is DARPA‚Äôs systems office responsible for all X-plane, spacecraft, ground vehicle, and robotics programs, totaling approximately $500 million annually. Paul also developed and led DARPA's advanced design and manufacturing program portfolio (called AVM‚ÄîAdaptive Vehicle Make), and also served as program manager for several space efforts, including the 100 Year Starship. For his work at DARPA, Paul was awarded the Distinguished Public Service Medal by the Office of the Secretary of Defense.

He has undergraduate and Master's degrees in aeronautics from MIT and Caltech, respectively, and a law degree from Georgetown University. Paul is also a licensed pilot.

name: Richard Thomas
title: Founder & CEO at Highlight - 25 years helping Enterprises and Service Providers work better together
about:
I'm the Founder and CEO of Highlight.

Over the last ten years we've watched the IT industry separate into two parts, like oil and water : companies that provide services; and companies that consume them. 

It should work. Enterprises want less involvement in their IT. They want to make shoes, sell cheeseburgers, run an airline. They're happy to let someone else handle the tech. And Providers are keen to step in. They want to deliver that technology, build a relationship, become the 'trusted advisor'.

Some Service Providers have figured out how to make this relationship work. The successful ones have realised you need a far greater level of conversation with your Enterprise customers, than the days when you just sold bandwidth or hosting. This conversation is now incredibly important, because both parties now depend on one another for the continued success of their business: for revenue, growth, stability, advice and feedback, and much more.

Highlight's mission is to facilitate that conversation. We provide a clear, uncluttered picture of how Providers are delivering IT services, and how Enterprises are using them: networks, infrastructure, applications and cloud services. Both sides - Service Provider and Enterprise - use the same tool, see the same information. Service Providers can win, understand, support, talk to and retain customers ; and those customers can manage their technology.

Personally, I sit on the engineering, technical side of life. I'm optimistic but pragmatic, I like taking on big problems, and building software people actually enjoy using. I like good coffee, sailing, and partnering with customers who share our love of delivering outstanding service. I think business success is largely about building the right team of people, and then stepping back and letting them get on with things. Management and leadership are skills you never stop learning - definitely not easy, but worth the effort.

name: Haokun Qin
title: Co-Founder @ Gale (YC W25) // modern business immigration
about:
Hi, I'm Haokun!

I'm a tech founder improving legal US immigration for businesses.

I was originally born in China, and immigrated to Canada at the age of 3.

Whenever my family would take a trip to China, it would always be a long manual process that would take weeks to complete.

And that too - the visitor process is relatively low stakes, what are immigrants going through?

I moved to the US for a YC batch, and realized that the US immigration law firms - while better -  are still operating with bureaucratic processes from manual form filling, to automatable LCA/PAF compliance done by hand.

I teamed up with my lifelong friends to build a better immigration platform for businesses - one that utilizes software to automate the manual processes of immigration, integrates with HRIS to automatically complete applications, and automates compliance updates.

By bringing modern tooling to immigration, we're able save teams 10+ hours per week in manual work, eliminate human error, and offer competitive rates for visas when compared to traditional law firms.

If you're also passionate about this or want to try it out, let's talk!

name: William Yang Wang
title: Founder & CEO, ChipAgents; Chair Professor at UC Santa Barbara
about:
William Wang is the Founder and CEO of Alpha Design AI, the maker of ChipAgents: an agentic AI environment that speeds up chip design and verification by 10x with your favorite code editor. ChipAgents has state-of-the-art results on NVIDIA's VerilogEval benchmark, and it is trusted by leading semiconductor companies that have shipped over 14B+ chips across the US, Europe, and Asia. For more, please visit chipagents.ai.

William Wang is also Director of UC Santa Barbara's Natural Language Processing group and Center for Responsible Machine Learning. He is the Duncan and Suzanne Mellichamp Endowed Chair Professor of Artificial Intelligence in the Department of Computer Science at the University of California, Santa Barbara. He received his PhD from the School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University. He has broad interests in Artificial Intelligence, including large language models and generative AI. He has published more than 200 papers at leading NLP/AI/ML conferences and journals, and received best paper awards (or nominations) at ASRU 2013, CIKM 2013, EMNLP 2015, and CVPR 2019, a DARPA Young Faculty Award (Class of 2018), an IEEE AI's 10 to Watch Award (Class of 2020), an NSF CAREER Award (2021), a British Computer Society - Karen Sp√§rck Jones Award (2022), a CRA-E Undergraduate Research Faculty Mentoring Award (2023), IEEE SPS Simon-Pierre Laplace Award (2024) and multiple Google Faculty Research Awards, IBM Faculty Awards, Facebook Research Awards, an Amazon AWS Machine Learning Research Award, Intel Faculty Grants, CISCO Faculty Award, JP Morgan Chase Faculty Research Awards, an Adobe Research Award, etc. He frequently serves as an Area Chair or Senior Area Chair for NAACL, ACL, EMNLP, and AAAI. He was an elected member of IEEE Speech and Language Processing Technical Committee (2021-2023) and a member of ACM Future of Computing Academy. In addition to research, William enjoys writing scientific articles that impact the broader online community. His work and opinions appear at major tech media outlets such as Wired, VICE, Scientific American, Fortune, Fast Company, NASDAQ, The Next Web, Law.com, and Mental Floss.

name: Casey Winters
title: Chief Evaluation Officer
about:
Hi, I‚Äôm Casey Winters, I help companies scale. I've worked on scaling multiple startups to large technology companies as an employee and as an advisor. Most recently, I was the Chief Product Officer at Eventbrite, where I led the PM, product design, research, and growth marketing teams. I helped Eventbrite navigate the pandemic and focus our strategy, becoming more product led, improving developer velocity, and making the shift to helping event creators grow their demand.

I started the marketing team at Grubhub and scaled Grubhub's demand side acquisition and retention strategies. We built a city expansion playbook and compounding loops of sustainable growth with low or no CAC and strong retention. This helped drive Grubhub from 3 cities to 1,000+ and from a $1 million series A to an IPO and $7.3 billion exit.

After this, I joined Pinterest and led the growth product team. I joined amid a shift from a social network to a personalized recommendations system, from social driven growth to SEO, and from U.S. only to international first. Pinterest had 40 million active users. We turned SEO into a scalable acquisition strategy, increased conversion to signups/mobile 5x, and replaced our email and notification system for scale. Pinterest now has over 400 million active users with the majority of them outside the U.S. and is valued at over $20 billion on the public market.

I started my career as a marketing analyst at Apartments.com, and that helped me understand that the way online companies grow is very different from what you learn about in school. From there, I started implementing these strategies at Apartments.com and sister site Homefinder.com.

My experience at all of these companies has taught me to seek out and solve for the bottlenecks that prevent companies from growing faster. Sometimes, it's that the teams aren't structured properly, or that they don't have access to the right data. Frequently, they just don't where to start because it's their first time scaling a company. I help these companies identify the right challenges to focus on and implement solutions from the CEO all the way down to ICs that allow for more sustained growth, and it's a lot of fun.

name: Asad Tirmizi
title: Founder T-robotics | Robotics Scientist
about:
My career has revolved around software frameworks for haptics and robotics. I am the founder of T-robotics, a company that trains AI skills for robots using end-to-end neural networks and constraint-based programming. Instead of general purpose models, that promise to make the robot do anything, we create specific purpose models that are small and agile and make robots great in a certain domain. These skills allow commercially available robots to fail less, perform complex tasks, and program easily. 

I am currently based in San Francisco, CA where T-robotics is headquartered. Previously, I have served as a robotics researcher at ByteDance Inc., Vicarious Inc. (acquired by Google), and Flanders Make. My research on haptics got the best Ph.D. award from the Italian Society of Researchers in Automatic Control (SIDRA). My subsequent research at Flanders Make on robot coworkers resulted in selection by EU as one of 15 Next Generation Innovators.

name: Michael Farber
title: Co-Founder & CEO at Breakout
about:
Hi, I'm an entrepreneur passionate about cities, storytelling, community development, & impact.

As the Founder of Breakout, I‚Äôve spent ten years building a nationwide community of changemakers from various backgrounds via transformative experiences driven by connection. We support this unique community through a network of support, resources, and platforms.

Since 2014, we have hosted multi-day experiences in 15+ cities and cultivated a vibrant community of 2,000+ mission-driven leaders across the United States. These experiences have invested over 3 million dollars directly into the community through flagship summits and local programming. We‚Äôve also created award-winning films telling the stories of incredible entrepreneurs, artists, & activists whom we've had the privilege of meeting through our work.

In 2017, I co-founded the Breakout Foundation, which empowers local leaders and entrepreneurs by providing them with a network of changemakers and unrestricted funding to support their communities. We've deployed over $400,000 in grants to 112 community leaders and social enterprises through the Breakout Foundation and advised on over 5 million philanthropic dollars invested in people & projects in communities we work with. 

In 2020, with the onset of the pandemic and IRL experiences on pause, we expanded our offerings from our proprietary programming to strategy and support to other mission-aligned organizations that wanted to tap our expertise around community, cities, and funding. This work has included working with mission-driven organizations such as Build in Tulsa, Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, Michigan Founders Fund, and Baker Tilly.

My entrepreneurial journey kicked off in 2009, when in the middle of the recession, I decided to walk away from an early career in commercial real estate at Cushman & Wakefield to join a new e-mail news start-up in the commercial real estate sector called Bisnow to grow their national events business. Over the next 4 1/2 years, the team grew from less than a dozen to 75 employees. I expanded the events business into key markets such as NYC, Texas, California, Chicago, Atlanta, and beyond and co-founded their national CEO retreat, Escape. In 2016, Bisnow was sold to Wicks Group.

Mr. Palmer is the Founder/Managing Director of Theseus Strategy Group.  He advises in complex transaction coordination/structuring; trusteeships and liquidations; strategy and business transformations; and "Special Situations" trading and liability strategies. Recent roles have included:

- Serving as Chief Strategy and Digital Officer for Quility Insurance, an insurance distribution and technology company.  Oversaw all aspects of corporate development, business transformation and strategy execution.  He also steered financial systems and incentives design and organizational alignment. Quility was named "Insurtech of the Year" and secured a significant minority investment. 

- Overseeing 363 asset sales, liability management and creditor recovery strategies, liquidating and litigation trusts and de-SPACing transactions, as well as structured venture capital investments.

- Chief Structuring Officer and an Investment Partner for MatlinPatterson, $13 billion global private equity franchise, responsible for structuring all transactions, targeted investments and liability management.  In this role, Mark devised and implemented many novel structures, set legal precedent and redefined legal and market standards across multiple investments and trading/investment strategies.

- Law Partner at Bracewell & Giuliani (Chair of Private Investment Funds/NY Corporate Practice), Linklaters (US Corporate Head) and Stroock & Stroock & Lavan (Corporate/Financial Restructuring), representing private investment firms, creditor committees, financial institutions and corporations on M&A, governance, takeovers, JVs, investments, financial restructurings and reorganizations.  He began his legal career at Sullivan & Cromwell as a Corporate and M&A Associate. 

- Entrepreneur/venture capitalist in Silicon Valley, serving as EVP/co-founder at NextSet Software, Director of Strategic Transactions at Reuters/Reuters Venture Capital and SVP/General Counsel for TIBCO Finance. 

Board representations have included Global Aviation, Advantix, FXI and Crescent Communities and the Idearc and the Boston Generating, Loot Crate and Old PSG litigation trusts.

He was graduated from Columbia University School of Law, where he was an Articles Editor on the Journal of Transnational Law, an Olin Fellow and Harlan Fiske Stone Scholar.  He served in the USNR as part of the Fleet Marine Force, including a mobilization for Operation Desert Storm.

name: Kevin J. Van Horn
title: Founder @ DecoverAI | Driving Legal Innovation with AI
about:
We‚Äôre living in the Fifth Industrial Revolution - a transformative time where the intersection of technology (AI/ML, Quantum, Blockchain) and human ingenuity are reshaping how we live, work, and connect. I‚Äôve spent over a decade helping organizations navigate growth, change, and complexity, and I co-founded DecoverAI to help leaders and their organizations cut through the noise, solve tough problems, and create real impact.

At DecoverAI, we are redefining how leaders and organizations navigate complexity. Having worked alongside government agencies and enterprise leaders across industries, I‚Äôve seen firsthand how outdated, siloed tools fail to meet the demands of modern legal workflows.

That‚Äôs why we built DecoverAI - the first AI-powered Legal Intelligence Platform (LIP) designed to help legal professionals make smarter decisions, faster. By integrating cutting-edge AI into every stage of legal work and not just improving efficiency - we‚Äôre transforming how legal teams operate.

The future of technology isn‚Äôt about adding more disconnected tools - it‚Äôs about building a truly connected platform that enables seamless collaboration, enhances accuracy, and unlocking opportunities for firms of all sizes. That‚Äôs exactly what we‚Äôre delivering at DecoverAI.

I believe real growth happens outside of comfort zones. Whether in business or life, challenges push us to innovate, evolve, and lead. It‚Äôs a philosophy that‚Äôs shaped me as an executive and as an individual - whether I‚Äôm cycling up steep climbs, diving into open water, skiing down mountains, lifting heavy weights, or occasionally jumping out of planes for a new perspective.

Beyond business, I‚Äôm deeply committed to giving back. I personally support causes like the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society, IRONMAN Foundation, NCMEC (National Center for Missing and Exploited Children), and HEROES (Honor Every Responsible Officer‚Äôs Eternal Sacrifice) - organizations that are making a tangible difference where it‚Äôs needed most. At DecoverAI, we‚Äôve implemented a 1-1-1 model, dedicating 1% of our time, 1% of our product, and 1% of our revenue to charitable initiatives, ensuring we leave a positive impact on the communities where we live and work.

The future is full of challenges and opportunities, and I‚Äôm here to embrace both. Let‚Äôs connect and explore how we can move forward, together.

name: Ravi Tandon
title: Co-Founder, CEO, DecoverAI
about:
With over a decade of engineering experience in software engineering, data analytics, and web development, I am passionate about creating innovative solutions that empower users to access, analyze, and visualize data with ease and speed. Currently, I am one of the co-founders and CEO of DecoverAI - a legal tech platform powered by Large Language Models. DecoverAI, a legal search engine that drastically improves insight discovery in the eDiscovery phase. I raised USD 2M in seed funding, built the initial product, hired and managed a team of three co-founders, and successfully launched multiple deployments with large legal teams. 

I also experimented with a consumer-facing legal search interface called MeraKanoon. Before that, I was a technical lead at Spotnana, where I architected the world's first travel-as-a-service platform, led a team of 25 engineers, and contributed to the company's valuation increase from USD 50M to USD 700M. I started my career as a staff software engineer at ThoughtSpot, where I played a pivotal role in developing their groundbreaking search functionality, revolutionizing business data access, and helping the company grow from USD 1M to USD 50M in ARR and from USD 100M to USD 4.2B in valuation. 

I have a master's degree in computer science from Princeton University, where I received a graduate fellowship and published a paper in the International Journal of Computer Networks and Communications. I am proficient in programming, Linux, and Python, and I enjoy learning new technologies and tools. I am also an avid reader, writer, and traveler, and I love to explore new cultures and perspectives.

name: Mike Farley

about:
Co-founder and former-CEO of Tile, a Silicon Valley company that is giving everything the power of smart location. I started Tile to help my wife find the (many, many) things she lost. Our first product is a small square that fits on your keychain, in your purse or on almost anything else, and uses Bluetooth to help you locate the things that matter to you most. We launched the company with a crowdfunding campaign and have since sold more than 15 million Tiles online and in retail stores such as Apple, Best Buy and Target. Tiles are available in multiple shapes and sizes and the Tile Smart Location Platform allows other companies to build smart location into their products. The Tile community spans nearly every country on the globe and locates more than 3 million items every day.

name: Jules Goldberg
title: Founder of Reviva | Inventor | Creator of apps including SnoreLab, Sleepwave, and Motionscape
about:
I‚Äôm the founder and tech inventor at Reviva, the company behind the top-rated health apps SnoreLab, Sleepwave, and Motionscape.

Reviva Softworks began in 2012 with the creation of my first app, SnoreLab. I coined the name to invoke the feeling ‚ÄòRevitalising Health with Software that Works‚Äô. As our journey evolved, so did our vision. Since 2019, we have made breakthrough discoveries in contactless motion sensing technology using inaudible pure tones which led to the creation of our newest apps: Sleepwave and Motionscape. Today, the ‚ÄòREV‚Äô in REVIVA invokes ‚ÄòRevolutionary‚Äô, whilst ‚ÄòVIVA‚Äô in many languages means ‚ÄòTO LIVE‚Äô!

My journey as an app developer began when my wife complained that I was snoring, and I became fascinated by the mysterious world of sleep that we can neither see nor hear. I taught myself to code and launched the first version of SnoreLab in 2012 with no external funding. Since then, the app has been downloaded over 15 million times, helping people around the world to understand and improve their sleep.

Reviva has grown to become a true ‚Äòfamily business‚Äô, run by myself and my wife, Vanessa, with a wonderful group of colleagues who are very much our family too. The company is financially self-sufficient with no external investment (and no, we aren‚Äôt looking for any!!).

For the past 5 -years, most of my time has been focussed on R&D, developing a family of technologies that we call PureTone, which is protected by an exceptional portfolio of patents. In 2022, we launched Sleepwave, a motion-sensing sleep tracker and smart alarm designed to wake people up feeling fresh. Our latest release, Motionscape, brings PureTone technology to the relaxation space with motion-sensing visualisations, games and breathing exercises that helps users engage with their breath in a more immersive way.

There is a lot more to come in the years ahead!

name: Cayden Pierce
title: Smart Glasses CEO/CTO @ Mentra
about:
Mentra is building the OS for smart glasses, the next computing platform.

Why build an OS for smart glasses?

Because the smart glasses hardware is finally ready. And the AI is ready. But the software is not, and building this OS is the last piece needed to unlock the next personal computer.

Why me?

Because I'm a transhumanist hacker that started building smart glasses over 6 years ago - I build systems to interface with and enhance the human mind.

And we can use smart glasses to do just that - upgrade our intelligence with AI. I believe they're the next massively adopted personal computing interface.

I've built smart glasses that sense our brains, augment our memories, and allow AI to inject ideas into our conversations.

Smart glasses to learn new languages faster, enhance doctors' decision making in the emergency room, and upgrade our conversations.

I like to say "I make cyborgs." But actually, we're already cyborgs.

And I may be cyborg Exhibit A. I built a mobile hacker lab RV to serve as an extension of my body. I existed as this cybernetic vehicle and drove across North America.

One stop along the way was Wolfram Research, where we tried to understand if LLMs represent meaning in the same way our brains do.

The last stop was MIT Media Lab where I built custom wearables and proactive AI agents with the aim to augment our cognition. 

And finally, today, I'm in SF and Shenzhen leading Mentra. We're building the OS and apps layer for the next personal computing interface. Check it out: https://Mentra.Glass.

Follow if you want to stay up on wearables, brain interfaces, and cyborg adventures.

name: Jhillika Kumar
title: Founder & CEO at Mentra | Neurodivergent | Forbes 30u30 | Building a Neuroinclusive #FutureOfWork. üåü
about:
Jhillika is the founder and CEO of Mentra, Georgia Tech founder, and honorary degree recipient, and previous Grace Hopper Keynote speaker for neurodiversity empowerment. 

Kumar is a neurodivergent whose passion for neurodiversity advocacy stems from her life experiences growing up as the sister of a nonspeaking autistic individual named Vikram and ADHDer herself. After 27 years of being unable to communicate his thoughts, Vikram learned how to type through an accessible letterboard. Uncovering his vast intelligence and eloquence inspired Kumar her to search for a solution to the need to empower those who society has overlooked. 

At Georgia Tech, Jhillika founded Mentra: the world‚Äôs largest neurodiversity employment network. After understanding the innate barriers to employment through community driven research, Mentra focused on the candidate experience to built a tech-platform that intelligently matches neurodiverse individuals with inclusive companies that value their unique abilities.

In 2019, Jhillika was recognized for her work and won the AbitaB.org Student of Vision Award, where she delivered a Keynote speech at Grace Hopper to an international audience of women in technology. In her captivating speech, she called upon the audience of 15,000 women and young girls to leverage the power of empathy and technology to enable the one billion people who live with some form of a disability today. In her video, she brought awareness to the neurodivergent community that is often sidelined by society‚Äôs policies, technologies and employment opportunities. 

In 2018, Jhillika delivered a TEDx talk where she shared ‚ÄúYou know what‚Äôs ironic is that I‚Äôve learned most of my lessons from a boy who has never spoken a word in his life, ever,‚Äù she told the TEDx audience. ‚ÄúAnd if there is anything at all that I would like to do in this lifetime, I would like to take the lessons my brother has taught me and show to you how much he, and the neurodivergent community, have to offer to this world.‚Äù

To learn more about the movement Mentra is starting to [neuro]diversify the workforce of the future, visit: www.mentra.me

name: Sadok Kohen

about:
After having worked for Microsoft as a software engineer for 4 years Sadok have decided to become an entrepreneur founding his first gaming startup in the year 2000.

He has then founded a Voip startup that has been acquired by the international telecommunication company Intelicom of which he became the CTO managing 4 million subscribers and more than 400 points of presence.

In 2005 Sadok decided to return to the gaming market in what became the biggest online poker startup of Turkey, oyunsalonu.com, valued at above $100 Million.

After the Turkish market was regulated, looking for new opportunities Sadok co-founded with Saran Holding, a large media group in Turkey, the first social betting venture in the world, tuttur.com, that has now gained a 15% market share against fierce competition. This success led the local media group to fund a digital section of which Sadok became the CEO. The first acquisition of this corporate entity being a sports portal which since the acquisition grew ten fold in becoming the second largest independent sports portal in the country.

In 2013 he took a role as head of innovation at bwin.com, largest betting company in the world as an outside counsel and startup products owner.

In this period Sadok also has made few angel investments: a gamification platform (actapi.com), a same day delivery service (kapgel.com) and a Edutech company (Twin Science). He also has recently took a board seat of xfire.com, a competitive esport tournament platform based in Los Angeles.

Sadok has launched a new worldwide startup called betbull.com in 2017, based on the success of the Turkish social betting platform, and innovative products he introduced to bwin.

Betbull has been acquired by Wynn Resorts and charged with Wynn's digital strategy across the United States under their brand WynnBET as co-founder and CPO.

Recently Sadok started PhilospherKing, and AI based narrative first gaming platform to unlock interactive story telling to the masses.

about:
Hi! üëãüèº I'm Shane Robinson, LinkedIn member #60,294 since December 2003.

So, where have I been for the last 21 years? 

Well, I‚Äôve been gainfully self-employed, diving into the world of digital innovation. For years, I saw LinkedIn as a place to find a job‚Äîwhich I didn‚Äôt need‚Äîso I only logged in occasionally. 

Until late 2022, I was the Co-Founder of Bare Feet Studios, LLC, alongside the incomparable Roxanne Darling. In 2002, we relocated BFS to the beautiful island of Oahu, Hawaii (and later to Maui in 2011), where we built a thriving social media and website consulting business, collaborating with companies and state agencies across the U.S. 

Through our award-winning, ahead-of-its-time (2006) video series "BeachWalks with Rox," we traveled the country, speaking and training at conferences on what‚Äôs now known as "Podcasts."

Fun fact: I was among the first 32 people in the world recording audio podcasts back in 2004. Adam Curry, the "Podfather," and Dave Winer created a directory and private message board for early "audio casters," and I was right there at the start.

Fast-forward to late 2022: Roxanne and I parted ways (still close friends and co-parents to our rescue pup, Mama Sita), and I've ventured out on my own while Roxanne continues to gradually wind down BFS after an incredible 28-year run (as of 2024).

Now, I‚Äôm channeling my 41 years of programming experience and 30 years as a Database & Information Systems Architect into creating cutting-edge, component-based, professional-grade Notion Information Management Systems through my new company, INEO Media, LLC.

On top of that, I‚Äôm embarking on a grand solo adventure, slow traveling the world full-time starting December 30, 2024. My first year will be spent exploring SE Asia: Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, and the Philippines.

I‚Äôll be documenting my journey as a Digital Nomad on two new YouTube channels:

@EasySlowTravel ‚Äì Your go-to for organized, well-planned full-time travel tips.

@MobileTravelCreator ‚Äì Tutorials and how-tos on the tools, software, and techniques for video shooting & editing that support EasySlowTravel. Plus, advice for anyone looking to systematize and streamline their productivity and content creation.

Subscribe to my newsletter to stay in the loop on beta tests for my Notion-based applications, special discounts, and travel itineraries:
https://shanerobinson.com/subscribe

name: Rohan Sukhdeo
title: Co-Founder and Builder @ Originalis
about:
Rohan Sukhdeo is a dedicated builder who has recently started to venture into the world of investing. His journey began in Queens, New York, where he grew up. He attended Townsend Harris High School, a top-ranked magnet school known for its rigorous humanities-focused curriculum. This strong foundation in humanities was complemented by his time at Columbia University, where he majored in Industrial Engineering and Operations Research.

At Columbia, Rohan found his true calling in technology and entrepreneurship. He was one of the lead developers for Columbia Spectator Publishing and actively participated in Columbia's Organization of Rising Entrepreneurs and the Application Development Initiative Labs, which solidified his passion for innovation and development.

After graduation, Rohan joined Citi as a Quant in the equity derivatives division. At Citi, he developed tools for trading and worked extensively on the equities C++ pricing library, enhancing the bank's trading strategies and risk management capabilities. His career took a significant turn when he joined Citi's selective internal startup incubator, the Markets Acceleration Lab. In this role, Rohan became the first developer on a small team working on building Citi's internal crypto analytics platform‚Äîdesigned for firm-wide adoption and eventually to be spun out as an enterprise SaaS product to be sold on Wall Street.

In parallel, Rohan was pursuing a Master‚Äôs in Computer Science at Georgia Tech, specializing in Machine Learning. He decided to leave the program to join Antler's startup accelerator, where he co-founded Enoki, a company focused on creating the "Figma for developers." This venture marked his deep engagement with the Linux open-source community and heightened his appreciation for open-source development. After a small exit from Enoki, Rohan is excited about continuing down the entrepreneurial path and exploring opportunities in challenging and high-barrier industries.

Rohan continues to be actively involved in open source, with an interest in AI agent development and its applications, particularly in the public and private capital markets spaces. His expertise spans AI, machine learning, Linux development, DevOps, and full-stack development.

Outside of work, Rohan loves sports, especially basketball, football, and cricket. He also enjoys running, participating in several 15ks and half-marathons across the country.

I help organizations stay irreplaceably human while strategically leveraging AI. Because your clients need you, not just efficiency.

Too many organizations are being sold on AI as a replacement strategy. Cut costs. Eliminate roles. Automate everything. My philosophy is simple: don't outsource your intuition.

‚Ä¢ Change management at a pace your organization and clients can trust

If you're tired of consultants who see people as cost centers to optimize, let's talk about making your team indispensable instead.

name: Beth Ann Lopez
title: Founder at Outfox Health | Custom AI copilots for health plans & employers | Harvard MPH | WEF Technology Pioneer
about:
I believe healthcare should be accessible and affordable for everyone. Yet healthcare is complicated. Costs are not transparent. The US spends the most on healthcare in the world while people are sicker than ever.

We created Outfox Health to empower people with transparency. We help you compare provider prices and understand your health benefits so you can make informed choices about your care.

How I got here:

‚Ä¢ Studied biochemistry at UNM. Took the MCAT and was ready for medical school until losing several family members to diabetes (including two aunts in their 30s). Was so frustrated by the poor quality of healthcare they received in rural New Mexico. As a 6th generation New Mexican, I joined the Peace Corps to gain perspective and worked at a clinic in Cambodia.

‚Ä¢ Realized that the root of most health problems isn't about medicine - it's about broken systems. Shifted my career goals and went to Harvard School of Public Health for graduate school.

‚Ä¢ Joined a tech startup and grew a platform for pharmacists to thousands of users within months. Got addicted to the speed and scale of digital health. Started my own tech company in Vietnam and helped millions of people get care.

My mission is to make healthcare understandable and transparent for all Americans.

Want to join the fight? Let's connect.

atlas.onl

name: Robin Shah
title: Co-Founder, Chief Executive Officer at Thyme Care
about:
Friends (and friends of friends) regularly reach out when a loved one is told they have cancer. All ask me the same question: ‚ÄúWhat do I do now?‚Äù ‚ÄúWhere should I go?‚Äù People seeking reassurance and answers during their most vulnerable moments shouldn't have to rely on an ‚Äúinsider‚Äù for guidance‚Äîand truthfully, most don't have access to an insider.   

At Thyme Care, we share a passion to create a better, more connected care experience for everyone affected by cancer. We built a value-based oncology model with an integrated ecosystem of care navigators, social workers, oncology groups, primary care groups, and health plans that put people first. Our approach connects providers, payers, and patients at every step, making cancer care easier to understand, navigate, and access. And our connected ecosystem with AI-powered navigation features provides support across the complete spectrum: through diagnosis, treatment, and recovery, while also addressing their mental, emotional, administrative, and socioeconomic needs. Our approach is driving a future in care where providers are preventative care strategists, payers are health optimization partners, patients are co-producers of their health, and digital technologies are core to healthcare infrastructure.

This work is deeply personal and fuels my passion for transforming healthcare systems. Before Thyme Care, I was a founding member of OneOncology (later acquired by TPG and AmerisourceBergen Corporation, now Cencora), where I focused on provider development, marketing, and technology integration. Earlier, I helped reshape how oncologists leverage real-world data at Flatiron Health (later acquired by Roche), and the beginning of my oncology journey started when helping manage my father's comprehensive community cancer center. 

These experiences have taught me that business success and societal impact go hand in hand. Whether it‚Äôs breaking down data silos to empower decision-making or addressing systemic barriers like access to transportation and mental health support for cancer patients, I‚Äôm driven by the idea that businesses can‚Äîand should‚Äîbe a force for good. 

Each experience has built upon the last, laying the foundation for my purpose and mission: identifying and creating connection points that catalyze meaningful change in healthcare.

name: Martin Bittner, MD, DPhil, MBA
title: CEO Redouble AI (YC S24)Ô∏±Automating complex workflows with AI
location: New York, New York, United States
about:
AI and the promises of what it can do seem to be everywhere - and yet, the reality inside companies speaks a very different language: 90% of pilots never make it to production, and the countless off-the-shelf AI tools that claim to be plug-and-play never deliver the promised RoI. But there is a better way:

I have spent the past decade developing automation solutions for complex enterprise workflows, seeing first-hand what it takes to automate the myriad of processes that drive biotech, pharma, and other highly regulated industries behind the scenes, and what leads to actual value creation. This is what I have learned, and the basis for what we build and deploy with our partners:

1) AI is inherently and categorically different from software - it is probabilistic, not deterministic, in nature, and thus requires a very different way of adoption that prioritizes ensuring dependability, reliability, and verifying the validity of its outputs.

2) AI's most powerful ability is also its Achilles heel - the ability to learn and adapt, from data, and from humans. This means adopting AI is more akin to hiring a junior employee, who needs training and oversight, but then becomes an invaluable member of your team. Human plus AI beats pure AI any day of the week. 

3) Each and every company is different - there is no "average company" for whom a generic solution will do. The key is using AI in a way that it mirrors and augments your current processes, instead of forcing the adoption of someone else's way of doing things. 

4) AI in isolation is useless - instead, its value is derived from being deeply integrated into your data and across your organization, so that it can actually help in your day to day. 

5) Regulated industries are paranoid about data privacy and security - and rightly so. Supporting comprehensive permissions, authorizations, and the most stringent security protocols is not optional, but a prerequisite from the get-go. 

About me: an MD-PhD-MBA by background, for the past ten years I have successfully been automating the most complex workflows in biopharma, healthcare, and financial services as a two-time founder - having built and led my first company all the way from inception to VC funding to profitability in the UK, and now leading my second YC-backed venture in the US. Dozens of private and public companies across the US, Europe, and Asia-Pacific work daily with the platforms whose creation I have led - as a trusted partner in successfully automating mission-critical processes and workflows.

We started besti because when we listen to Gen Z, we hear the same wishlist we had starting out. Gen Z wants & needs more support to achieve their career goals. They‚Äôve grown up in a world where knowledge of anything is available anywhere, anytime. Yet the workplace remains a black box. 

Gen Z‚Äôs dissatisfaction is causing companies to lose millions due to low productivity, high turnover and mounting burnout. besti directly solves these problems by transforming how employees learn and get support at work. They get the skills to remain engaged & become high performing; companies get higher output and a more committed workforce. 

Everybody wins.

name: Martin Basiri
title: >>Want to educate the world? Join us!<<
about:
Martin Basiri is Founder and CEO of Passage, which enables immigrants and international students by providing financial access, and Co-Founder and former CEO of ApplyBoard, the world‚Äôs largest online international student recruitment platform. Martin, an inventor from a young age, founded his first startup during his undergraduate studies in Iran, where he created and sold six different inventions. His own international student journey began in 2010 where he got his Masters in Mechatronics Engineering from the University of Waterloo. Realizing the opportunity international students had at their fingertips, he helped his brothers, Meti and Massi, navigate the same complex process of applying to study abroad, and the three of them founded ApplyBoard in 2015. 

Martin served as CEO of ApplyBoard from 2015 to 2022. Under his leadership ApplyBoard grew to a team of 1500+ assisting more than 1M students with their study abroad journey from more than 130 countries. During this time ApplyBoard partnered with over 1,600+ schools across Canada, US, UK, Australia and Ireland. ApplyBoard was named the fastest growing tech company in Canada and became globally recognized with a valuation of over $3B, and attracting $500 million in investments. 

At ApplyBoard, Martin noticed a limitation. There were many deserving students who he wished to help who did not have the financial means to do so. Driven by his commitment and passion for the mission of ‚Äúeducating the world‚Äù, he started Passage in 2023. Passage‚Äôs goal is to provide financial access for deserving individuals that - through no fault of their own - grew up without the means to fulfill their potential. Continuing and augmenting his work at ApplyBoard as a board member, Martin now is building the financial infrastructure for smart immigration so that anyone with the drive and aspiration can radically change their lives through social mobility.

name: David Kaiser
title: Co-Founder & CEO of Scienza Health (formerly MemoryCareAI)-empowering clinicians and workplace leaders with AI-driven early detection to combat cognitive impairment and boost workforce well-being.
about:
Scienza Health (formerly MemoryCareAI) is redefining how the world detects, monitors, and manages cognitive and behavioral health conditions‚Äîusing voice.

Our patented, AI-powered voice-to-voice platform leverages over 2 million closed-source longitudinal patient records‚Äîone of the largest proprietary datasets in Alzheimer's, Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI), and behavioral health. This foundation enables clinically validated, real-time analysis of over 2,500 speech biomarkers to detect early signs of cognitive decline, depression, anxiety, PTSD, and more.

Scienza automates the entire patient interaction workflow‚Äîfrom intake to documentation. Our platform performs full patient intake conversations, schedules appointments, conducts follow-ups and check-ins, assigns CPT codes, and transcribes directly into the EMR. No more phone tag. No more paperwork bottlenecks. Just faster, smarter care.

With seamless integration into wearables and EHR systems, Scienza enables proactive monitoring, predictive insights, and personalized interventions‚Äîreducing time to diagnosis and increasing profitability for healthcare providers.

We're not building the future of cognitive care‚Äîwe're deploying it.

With over 20 years of executive leadership in behavioral healthcare and a track record of launching successful ventures, I am deeply committed to blending innovative technology with compassionate care. Our mission is to bring early detection and tailored treatment into every home. Whether you‚Äôre a patient seeking early intervention, a healthcare or pharmaceutical leader in need of actionable data, or an investor looking for scalable, impactful innovation, I invite you to join us in reshaping the future of cognitive healthcare.

name: Toly Sherbakov
title: We help small teams get work done without needing a dedicated project manager using productivity tool Casy.
about:
Let‚Äôs do this. I‚Äôm Toly Sherbakov, founder, builder, and probably the guy who‚Äôs failed more times than he‚Äôs won. But hey, that‚Äôs the game.

‚≠êÔ∏è Right now, I‚Äôm in California, launching Casy‚Äîa simple workspace for freelancers and small teams. More on that soon.
But let me backtrack a bit:

In 2014, I joined a team building AR stuff, and by 2015, we launched Awespace, a custom AR/VR studio. We worked with a billionaire, sure, but the projects for kids and museums? That‚Äôs where the magic was.

2017 came, and we launched Faradise‚Äîan AR furniture marketplace. Raised $1.5M. A year later, we got acqui-hired. Boom, team sold off, product handed over. Quick exit, but we weren‚Äôt done yet.

In 2019, we relaunched Faradise in the US, got into an accelerator, raised more cash, started making money... and six months later, we had to shut it down. Lesson: Money doesn‚Äôt solve everything.

By 2020, we pivoted, brought back the studio as Magic Quick, and launched Magic Kids, an educational game for 4-8-year-olds. Raised $500k, got on CBS, Fox News, ABC. Things were looking up.

In 2022, we launched Magic Playbox for custom AR/VR products. It did OK, but we paused it after a year. Not every idea is a winner.

And in 2024, we made the call to shut down Magic Kids. That‚Äôll be a separate post. Lessons, struggles, the whole thing.

üëÄ A couple of extra facts:
Got my O-1 visa to the US in 2021 (apparently, I‚Äôm ‚Äúextraordinary,‚Äù or so the paperwork says).
Never applied to Forbes 30under30 or any of that hype.
Ditched my PhD to chase startups full time.

Now, I‚Äôm 33, starting Casy, and the journey‚Äôs just getting crazier. I‚Äôm ready for the wins‚Äîand the inevitable failures along the way. "I‚Äôll believe in each day like a mom believes in her kid."
Let‚Äôs roll ‚ö°Ô∏è

name: Timothy Marks

name: Aaron Klein
title: Founder at Contio. On a mission to kill broken meetings.
about:
Aaron Klein‚Äôs professional career has been marked as a builder ‚Äî of companies, of teams, of organizational culture, and of software beloved by customers.

In 2025, he founded Contio, the company on a mission to kill broken meetings. Unlike the AI notetakers that record the misery and send you emails about it, the Contio MeetingOS empowers people to create snappier, smarter, and action-packed meetings.

Prior to Contio, Klein was the founding CEO of Riskalyze, which started in his basement in 2011. It rebranded as Nitrogen after Hg Capital became its majority owner in 2021. He led the company through 42 consecutive quarters of growth, scaling to serve tens of thousands of financial advisors, and twice being named one of the world‚Äôs 10 most innovative companies in finance by Fast Company Magazine. He passed the baton to his successor in 2023, and continues to serve on the firm‚Äôs Board of Directors.

Aaron is married to Cacey Klein, and they are parents to an amazing Korean-Ethiopian-American family that consists of Spencer, Emma and Teddy. Together, they cofounded Hope Takes Root, an initiative to use capitalism to change the future for orphans and at-risk kids in Ethiopia. They reside in Eagle, Idaho, and absolutely love it.

Aaron also sits on the board of Mountain States Policy Center, a bipartisan think tank advancing free markets in public policy. Previously, he was elected three times to serve as a community college trustee, serving from 2004 to 2016. Investment News has named him one of the industry‚Äôs top 40 under 40 executives, and the Wealth Management Industry Awards honored him as CEO of the Year in 2023.

name: Brooks Powell
title: CEO @ Cheers | $70m revenue, #1 on Amazon, 30k retail locations, & 75% YoY Growth! ü•Çüçæ
about:
I started Cheers nearly a decade ago while I was a student at Princeton University. After reading about the discovery of the alcohol-related properties of our hero ingredient, DHM, I couldn't think about anything else. Within 2 weeks, I decided to make a major career change, from Baptist minister to entrepreneur, and dropped everything to begin working on Cheers. 

I knew DHM was the future for the alcohol industry, and I believed that I had a unique responsibility to bring it to market in an ethical way. Starting in 2014, Cheers became the first company selling purified DHM at scale in the United States.

While getting this DHM formula into the hands of drinkers is a good thing, how you bring it to market is of the utmost importance. The fact of the matter is that even responsible drinking can lead to feeling less than 100% the next day. I believed that we could promote the use of DHM in a responsible way and ultimately create a category called "alcohol-related health"‚Äîwhich Cheers would be the crown of. 

Our human studies with DHM revealed that it was most effective when combined with cysteine and other ingredients. Today, these formulas are covered by US patent #9,603,830 (granted). Our big, hairy, audacious goal is "A Billion Better Mornings by 2035." With 25 million doses already sold, we're 2.5% there already.

When used in a proper way, alcohol is a good thing through its ability to bring people together. We work each day to promote the good of alcohol while reducing the bad. Our mission is "bringing people together through promoting fun, responsible, and health-conscious alcohol consumption." Our vision is "a world where everyone can enjoy alcohol throughout a long, healthy, and happy lifetime."

Cheers is a force for good beyond the health benefits of its products. We are building a generation of ‚Äúsmarter drinkers‚Äù who know more about alcohol, ways to be responsible with it, and how to make room for it by being healthier in other areas of their life‚Äîsuch as eating less sugar, more fiber, opting for healthier fats, and exercising more. As we like to say: ‚ÄúYou need to earn your right to drink.‚Äù

While I started Cheers, today the company is filled with some of my best friends and lieutenants who have made the company their own. Cheers has expanded far beyond myself. It's our team, our shareholders, our network of partners, and most importantly our customers that make this company great. I couldn't be more grateful for the loyalty and joy that we have built around Cheers. 

See more at cheershealth.com/about and cheershealth.com/investor-relations.

Khylir Patton is a proud HBCU graduate, a mother of two under two, and the founder of a maternal wellness app‚Äîa mobile platform designed to close the maternal healthcare gap.

After launching and managing two small businesses in real estate and hospitality, she returned to her passion for supporting others‚Äîthis time from the lens of motherhood.
The idea was born from Khylir‚Äôs own experience: during pregnancy, she found herself overwhelmed, unsupported, and spending long nights searching online for answers and care options. A particularly frustrating attempt to find a proper prenatal massage highlighted the glaring gap in maternal support systems. Her second pregnancy, which she experienced through home-based midwifery care, was calm, personalized, and healing‚Äîproving that a better model exists.
Khylir created the maternal wellness app to bring that model to every mom‚Äîespecially those who often feel unseen. She envisions a world where care is accessible, culturally competent, and brought right to a mother‚Äôs doorstep. Her leadership is guided by compassion, advocacy, and a deep reverence for the power of women. Khylir is not just building an app‚Äîshe‚Äôs rebuilding the village.
